  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Criminal organizations historically sought ways to disguise illegal income\n\n2. Initial Legal Frameworks:\n- US Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report cash transactions over $10,000\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global issue\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Turning Points:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Made money laundering a federal crime\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n5. Contemporary Approach:\n- Comprehensive international regulatory frameworks\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence regulations\n\nThe legal landscape continues to evolve with technological advancements and emerging financial technologies.",
